Unrestrained Central Bank Governor?
Prague—Recently, one-sided criticism of central banks in developed countries has become fashionable.
The main points of criticism are roughly as follows: since 2008, monetary policymakers have been too active, their authority has expanded too quickly, and they are endangering the economy.
This claim — strangely, it is popular among ideological camps that should be irreconcilable, such as liberals and neo-Marxists — is profoundly mistaken.
Critics have failed to understand that modern central banks are not only responsible for curbing inflation but also for maintaining long-term price stability.
Price levels are like a person's body temperature, which can fluctuate within a range that is neither too high nor too low without causing serious symptoms.
Central banks must be equally "active" when combating deflation caused by weak demand and curbing high inflation driven by excessive demand.
Although the fighting was entirely symmetric, the public's assessment of it was strangely severely biased, especially in countries where the people are financially very conservative.
This includes my homeland, the Czech Republic. Czech savers have very small savings, and the loan-deposit ratio remains far below 100%.
Czechs are concerned about inflation, even though the inflation rate in the Czech Republic reached a 13-year low last year, and since 2013, when I served as the Deputy Governor, the Czech National Bank has been committed to eliminating deflation risks.
Another common complaint about the policies of central banks in developed countries since 2008 is that these policies have generated redistributive effects.
Of course it would, but so what?
Any monetary policy action redistributes wealth.
Raising interest rates pleases savers, while cutting interest rates benefits borrowers.
Importers prefer a strong exchange rate; exporters prefer a weak exchange rate.
For monetary policy to be effective, it must have different effects on different groups at different times.
This is not a mistake; this is the nature of monetary policy.
Some critics also argue that central banks, regardless of whether they have achieved their inflation targets, have made their activism not only unnecessary but also ineffective.
At times, they even place these contradictory criticisms in a single sentence, as if they were accusing someone of firing blanks yet causing casualties.
The reality is that central banks around the world successfully maintained price stability and the purchasing power of money during and after the global financial crisis — and it was an unequivocally remarkable success.
Without their intervention, their economies would have faced catastrophic deflation, a sharp drop in asset prices, and a complete collapse of both the financial and real sectors.
Clearly, decisive action was the right approach to dealing with the crisis (what role central banks played in the outbreak of the financial crisis is another issue).
In a system using a flexible currency without intrinsic value, the quantity of money must change over time in order for the purchasing power of money to remain roughly constant.
Therefore, price stability, rather than the quantity of money, is the important issue.
The expansion of central bank balance sheets reflects the depth of problems faced by many economies after 2008.
In this context, central banks took the necessary measures to maintain purchasing power and price stability.
For them, there is no "activism" here; only the eternal mandate of a mission that needs to be fulfilled.
If you find this assertion to be arrogant, let me provide some evidence.
People vote with their wallets.
If the purchasing power of their money was severely damaged after 2008, they naturally sought to exchange their currency (for other currencies, precious metals, or other forms of savings).
This is rare in the developed world.
Of course, central banks in many countries have not met their inflation targets.
(Central banks typically define the ideal economic "temperature" as an annual inflation rate of around 2%.
) But this is certainly unpleasant, it does not lead to catastrophe, especially considering that the decline in prices is partly due to supply—rather than demand—shocks, such as a sharp fall in oil prices.
This shock benefits consumers and poses no threat to price stability, at least for net oil importing countries.
Consider this scenario.
A company plans to increase its sales by 2%, but the manager achieves this only through a 1% annual increase over two consecutive years.
Would you consider this company a failure?
I fear not.
After all, private companies' planned and actual profits and revenues can easily deviate by 10% or more.
Most businesses have fewer variables affecting their operating environment than central banks.
Given that, how can you expect central banks to always achieve precise inflation targets regardless of the economic environment?
It must be clarified that I am not saying central banks should not strive to work toward their targets.
They absolutely should.
Additionally, they absolutely should not allow inflation expectations to become unstable.
But when judging central banks, people need to maintain proper restraint.
They indeed need to stop saying untrue things — such as, the central bank's policy toolkit is not only possibly exhausted, but is already nearing exhaustion.
Monetary policymakers have ample weapons and unlimited ammunition at their disposal to use as they see fit.
These weapons have different calibers and their effectiveness varies at different times.
Not all weapons are suitable for all situations in all economies.
But the central bank's ability to create and destroy money is theoretically unlimited.
Central bank governors should say "enough" to the ignorant criticism they face.
None of our critics have been able to explain in a clear and credible way why price stability is the wrong objective, what key objective central banks should pursue instead, and what radically different approaches they should have taken since 2008.
There is a very simple reason for this: the policies adopted by central banks in developed countries since the crisis have been the correct ones.
In fact, this policy pulled our economy back from the edge of the cliff.
You're welcome.
